# --- Document tooling (from AIMS Desktop heritage) -------------------
# pandoc — universal document converter (MD↔PDF↔DOCX↔HTML↔TeX). The
#     single most-cited "Why don't you ship X" gap in AIMS Desktop
#     2020's package list; used by every modern academic workflow.
# pdftk-java — split / merge / rotate PDFs, fill forms. The legacy
#     `pdftk` is a transitional package in Trixie that depends on
#     pdftk-java, so we depend on the real one directly.
# tilix — tabbed, tiling-capable terminal emulator. AIMS Desktop
#     2020 listed it as the recommended terminal.
# yt-dlp — youtube-dl's actively-maintained fork (youtube-dl itself
#     was archived). Used for offline lecture downloads in low-
#     bandwidth conditions.
 pandoc,
 pdftk-java,
 tilix,
 yt-dlp,
 gnome-screenshot,
 flameshot,
# --- Web & Android Development (course requirement) -----------------
# Covers the 2025-2026 "Web and Android Development" course.
# NOTE: nodejs is NOT pulled here. Trixie ships Node.js 20.19 which is
# EOL in April 2026 — already dead by ship time. The chroot hook
# 0095-nodesource swaps it out for Node 22 LTS from NodeSource (Active
# until April 2027). We list nodejs in the Description for visibility.
# default-jdk — Java 21 (Trixie's default JDK); required to run
#     Android Studio and Gradle. Also covers the JVM half of the
#     Web course (Spring Boot, Tomcat).
# gradle — Android's official build tool. The Android Studio bundle
#     uses its own gradle-wrapper but having a system gradle lets
#     command-line builds work offline.
# kotlin — Android's official language since 2019; pulled separately
#     because Android Studio's embedded Kotlin is bundle-only.
# php-cli + composer — for the legacy LAMP half of the course
#     (Laravel, Symfony, vanilla PHP).
# android-tools-adb / -fastboot — flash and debug Android devices
#     over USB for the Android Development course's hardware labs.
# Note: Android Studio itself is install-on-demand via Flatpak
# (com.google.AndroidStudio on Flathub) — apt-shipping it would
# pin it to whatever version Debian Trixie froze at release.
# Cursor (AI editor) and VSCodium (libre VS Code) are installed via
# chroot hooks 0096/0097 from upstream apt repos / .deb downloads.
# Bun, Deno and uv come via hook 0099 (binary releases).
 default-jdk,
 gradle,
 kotlin,
 php-cli,
 composer,
 android-tools-adb,
 android-tools-fastboot,
# --- Containers & orchestration (Web/Android, MLOps, Big Data) -------
# docker.io — Docker Engine from Debian (Moby). 26.1.5 in Trixie;
#     stable across the LTS window. Pulls containerd as a dep.
# docker-compose — note: this Trixie package is COMPOSE V2 (the Go
#     binary, version 2.26.1), not the deprecated Python v1. Debian
#     kept the legacy name `docker-compose`. Invoked as
#     `docker compose ...` (no dash).
# docker-buildx — multi-arch / multi-stage container builds.
# podman — daemonless, rootless container runtime; alternative to
#     docker.io that students may prefer in lab environments.
# kubectl — Kubernetes CLI (v1.32 in Trixie). Pairs with cloud /
#     MLOps modules.
# ansible — automation / Web Dev deployment workflows.
 docker.io,
 docker-compose,
 docker-buildx,
 podman,
 kubectl,
 ansible,
# --- Modern dev CLI --------------------------------------------------
# neovim — modern vim alternative (preferred by many TUI workflows).
# httpie — human-friendly curl replacement for API testing.
# rustup — Rust toolchain manager (manages stable/nightly toolchains).
#     Trixie also ships rustc 1.85 directly — we keep rustup for
#     users who need a newer toolchain on demand.
 neovim,
 httpie,
 rustup,
# --- Local DB labs (Database course) ---------------------------------
# redis-server complements redis-tools (client) — labs need a local
#     instance to push/pull from. Postgres / MariaDB clients are in
#     aims-os-math; their daemons stay out (labs use remote hosts).
 redis-server,
# --- Multimedia codecs (free + non-free) -----------------------------
 gstreamer1.0-plugins-base,
 gstreamer1.0-plugins-good,
 gstreamer1.0-plugins-bad,
 gstreamer1.0-plugins-ugly,
 gstreamer1.0-libav,
# --- Non-free codecs (Recommends, not Depends) -----------------------
# p7zip-rar lives in the Debian non-free component, so a standalone
# apt install on a vanilla Debian without non-free enabled would fail.
# On the AIMS OS ISO, live-build enables non-free in its source list
# so apt pulls this in automatically via Recommends like a Depends.
# Users on an apt-repo-only setup get the install regardless and can
# add p7zip-rar later if they need to open .rar archives.
Recommends:
 p7zip-rar,
Description: AIMS OS — GNOME desktop, installer and user applications
 This metapackage installs the AIMS OS user-facing layer: the GNOME
 desktop (task-gnome-desktop scope — desktop shell, GDM, Files, Web,
 Terminal — without the gnome metapackage's games and bloat), the
 Calamares graphical installer plus its Debian settings, the Plymouth
 boot splash framework (themed by aims-os-branding), Firefox ESR and
 Chromium with French and English locales, the complete LibreOffice
 suite with French and English dictionaries and thesauri, the standard
 GNOME tools (Evince, GIMP, Inkscape, Shotwell, VLC, GNOME Text
 Editor, Evolution), Flatpak with the GNOME Software plugin (Flathub
 remote registered by an AIMS-specific first-boot service), the
 NetworkManager stack with OpenVPN support, a small set of useful
 utilities (KeepassXC, ghostwriter, fish, zsh, ripgrep, fzf, bat,
 p7zip, screenshots), the web and Android development stack
 (OpenJDK 21, Gradle, Kotlin, PHP, Composer, adb/fastboot — plus
 Node.js 22 LTS, Bun, Deno, Cursor and VSCodium installed via
 chroot hooks since they're not in Trixie main or are EOL there),
 a container / orchestration stack (Docker Engine + Compose v2 +
 Buildx, Podman, kubectl, Ansible) for the 2025-2026 Web/Android
 Development and MLOps workflows, a local Redis server for the
 Database course's labs, modern dev CLI tools (neovim, httpie,
 rustup), DBeaver CE (universal SQL GUI installed via upstream apt
 repo), and the GStreamer codecs for media playback.
 .
 The fr_FR.UTF-8 locale and Africa/Dakar timezone are configured at
 the system level by aims-os-core; this metapackage adds the matching
 French desktop locales for LibreOffice, Firefox, hunspell, hyphen
 and mythes.
